The ground-state energy ($n=1$) of hydrogen is $-13.6 \, \mathrm{eV}$. The energy of positronium can be related to that of hydrogen by considering the reduced mass. For hydrogen, $\mu = \frac{m_e m_p}{m_e + m_p} \approx m_e$ because $m_p \gg m_e$. Thus, the ground-state energy of hydrogen is $E_1 = -\frac{m_e e^4}{8 \epsilon_0^2 h^2}$. For positronium, the ground-state energy is $E_{1, \text{Ps}} = -\frac{\mu e^4}{8 \epsilon_0^2 h^2} = -\frac{(m_e/2) e^4}{8 \epsilon_0^2 h^2}$.

